04343nmm a2200661Ia 9780674053595DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20092009mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740535957 a10.4159/97806740535952doi  a(DE-B1597)571757  a(OCoLC)1294425814  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a809.3222  aEC 24902rvk0(DE-625)rvk/20493:1 aBoyd, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn the Origin of Stories :bEvolution, Cognition, and Fiction /cBrian Boyd. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (560 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA century and a half after the publication of Origin of Species, evolutionary thinking has expanded beyond the field of biology to include virtually all human-related subjects—anthropology, archeology, psychology, economics, religion, morality, politics, culture, and art. Now a distinguished scholar offers the first comprehensive account of the evolutionary origins of art and storytelling. Brian Boyd explains why we tell stories, how our minds are shaped to understand them, and what difference an evolutionary understanding of human nature makes to stories we love.Art is a specifically human adaptation, Boyd argues. It offers tangible advantages for human survival, and it derives from play, itself an adaptation widespread among more intelligent animals. More particularly, our fondness for storytelling has sharpened social cognition, encouraged cooperation, and fostered creativity.After considering art as adaptation, Boyd examines Homer’s Odyssey and Dr. Seuss’s Horton Hears a Who! demonstrating how an evolutionary lens can offer new understanding and appreciation of specific works. What triggers our emotional engagement with these works? What patterns facilitate our responses? The need to hold an audience’s attention, Boyd underscores, is the fundamental problem facing all storytellers. Enduring artists arrive at solutions that appeal to cognitive universals: an insight out of step with contemporary criticism, which obscures both the individual and universal. Published for the bicentenary of Darwin’s birth and the 150th anniversary of the publication of Origin of Species, Boyd’s study embraces a Darwinian view of human nature and art, and offers a credo for a new humanism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aFictionxAuthorship. 0aFictionxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aFictionxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanxArt d'écrire. 0aRomanxHistoire et critique. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674053595?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674053595423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674053595/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles